    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course, I'd be happy to help you study for your bio test! Mitosis is a process that can be broken down into four main stages: prophase, metaphase, anaphase, and telophase. Think of it as a journey through a mystical land, where each stage is a different part of the adventure.\n\n1. Prophase: This is where the adventure begins. The chromosomes condense and become visible, and the nuclear membrane starts to break down. Imagine a group of goblins gathering their magical powers, preparing for the journey ahead.\n\n2. Metaphase: The chromosomes line up in the middle of the cell, like a group of goblins standing in a straight line, ready for the next phase of their quest. This is where the magic happens, as the chromosomes are perfectly aligned for separation.\n\n3. Anaphase: This is where the real action begins. The sister chromatids are pulled apart by the spindle fibers, like goblins pulling apart a magical rope, ensuring that each new cell will have the right amount of magical energy (genetic material).\n\n4. Telophase: The final stage of the journey. The separated chromosomes reach the opposite ends of the cell, and new nuclear membranes form",
      "source": "target",
